# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: granular-synthesis
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] In sound and music, an **envelope** describes how a sound changes over time.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] For example, a piano key, when struck and held, creates a near-immediate initial sound which gradually decreases in volume to zero.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] An envelope may relate to elements such as amplitude (volume), frequency (with the use of filters) or pitch.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The envelope generator was created by the American engineer Robert Moog, the creator of the Moog synthesizer, in the 1960s.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The composer Herbert Deutsch suggested Moog find a way to articulate his synthesizer so notes did not simply trigger on and off.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Moog wired a doorbell button to the synthesizer and used a capacitor to store and slowly release voltage produced from hitting a key.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] He refined the design to remove the need to push a separate button with every keypress, with two switches on every key: one to produce the control voltage determining pitch and the other to trigger the envelope generator.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The envelope generator became a standard feature of synthesizers.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] These were later simplified to the modern ADSR form (attack time, decay time, sustain level, release time) by ARP.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The most common kind of envelope generator has four stages: attack, decay, sustain, and release (ADSR).
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] While attack, decay, and release refer to time, sustain refers to level.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Some electronic musical instruments can invert the ADSR envelope, reversing the behavior of the normal ADSR envelope.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] During the attack phase, the modulated sound parameter fades from the maximum amplitude to zero then, during the decay phase, rises to the value specified by the sustain parameter.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] After the key has been released the sound parameter rises from sustain amplitude back to maximum amplitude.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Some envelopes, such as that of the Korg MS-20, have an extra parameter, hold.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] This holds notes at the sustain level for a fixed length of time before decaying.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The General Instrument AY-3-8910 sound chip includes only a hold time parameter; the sustain level is not programmable.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Another common variation in the same vein is the AHDSR (attack, hold, decay, sustain, release) envelope, in which the *hold* parameter controls how long the envelope stays at full volume before entering the decay phase.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Multiple attack, decay and release settings may be found on more sophisticated models.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Certain synthesizers also allow for a *delay* parameter before the *attack*.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Modern synthesizers, such as the Prophet '08, have DADSR (delay, attack, decay, sustain, release) envelopes.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] The delay setting determines the length of silence between hitting a note and the attack.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] Some software synthesizers, such as Image-Line's 3xOSC (included with their DAW FL Studio) have DAHDSR (delay, attack, hold, decay, sustain, release) envelopes.
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] A common feature on many synthesizers is an AD envelope (attack and decay only).
[src:granular-synthesis/envelope-music] This can be used to control, for example, the pitch of one oscillator, which in turn may be synchronized with another oscillator by oscillator sync.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] It is based on the same principle as sampling.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] However, the samples are split into small pieces of around 1 to 100 ms in duration, called **grains**.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Multiple grains may be layered on top of each other, and may play at different speeds, phases, volume, and frequency, among other parameters.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] At low speeds of playback, the result is a kind of soundscape, often described as a cloud, that is manipulated in a manner unlike that of natural sound sampling or other synthesis techniques.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] At high speeds, the result is heard as a note or notes of a novel timbre.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] By varying the waveform, envelope, duration, spatial position, and density of the grains, many different sounds can be produced.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Both have been used for musical purposes: as sound effects, raw material for further processing by other synthesis or digital signal processing effects, or as complete musical works in their own right.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Conventional effects that can be achieved include amplitude modulation and time stretching.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] More experimentally, stereo or multichannel scattering, random reordering, disintegration and morphing are possible.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] In 1947, Dennis Gabor introduced the idea that sounds can be represented by a series of elementary "grains," each grain being a short pulse containing both temporal and frequency information.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Greek-French composer Iannis Xenakis is known as the inventor of granular synthesis, having expanded upon Gabor's theoretical foundation.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] American composer Curtis Roads was the first to implement granular synthesis on a computer in 1974.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] In 1986, Canadian composer Barry Truax implemented real-time granular synthesis using the DMX-1000 Signal Processing Computer.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] This includes all sounds on the time scale shorter than musical notes, the sound object time scale, and longer than the sample time scale.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Specifically, this is shorter than one tenth of a second and longer than 10 milliseconds, which includes part of the audio frequency range (20 Hz to 20 kHz) as well as part of the infrasonic frequency range (below 20 Hz, rhythm).
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] In the frequency domain they may be named kernel, logon, and frame, among others.
[src:granular-synthesis/granular-synthesis] Micromontage is musical montage with microsound.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] "putting together") or **sound collage** ("gluing together") is a technique where newly branded sound objects or compositions, including songs, are created from collage, also known as musique concrète.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] This is often done through the use of sampling, while some sound collages are produced by gluing together sectors of different vinyl records.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Like its visual cousin, sound collage works may have a completely different effect than that of the component parts, even if the original parts are recognizable or from a single source.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Audio collage was a feature of the audio art of John Cage, Fluxus, postmodern hip-hop and postconceptual digital art.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] What made their technique true collage, however, was the juxtaposition of quotations and unrelated melodies, either by layering them or by moving between them in quick succession.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] A first documented instance of sound collage created as electronic music is *Wochenende* (in English, *Weekend*), a collage of words, music and sounds created by film-maker and media artist Walter Ruttmann in 1928.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Later, in 1948, Pierre Schaeffer used the techniques of sound collage to create the first piece of musique concrète, *Étude aux chemins de fer*, which was assembled from recordings of trains.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Schaeffer created this piece by recording sounds of trains onto several vinyl records, some of which had lock grooves allowing them to play in a continuous loop.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] He then set up multiple turntables in his studio, allowing him to trigger and mix together the various train sounds as needed.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Cage began in 1939 to create a series of found sounds works that explored his stated aims, the first being *Imaginary Landscape #1* for instruments including two variable speed turntables with frequency recordings.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] Important modern sound collage pieces were created by Pierre Schaeffer and the Groupe de Recherches Musicales.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] In 1950s and early-1960s Schaeffer, Pierre Henry, Olivier Messiaen, Pierre Boulez, Jean Barraqué, Karlheinz Stockhausen, Edgard Varèse, Iannis Xenakis, Michel Philippot, and Arthur Honegger all worked with sound collage.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] In 1954 Varèse and Honegger created *Déserts* and *La rivière endormie*".
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] John Cage created his influential collage piece *Williams Mix* in 1952.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] More recently, George Rochberg used collage in *Contra Mortem et Tempus* and *Symphony No.
[src:granular-synthesis/micromontage] In the 1980s Minóy made many palimpsest-like multi-tracked soundscape compositions that used sound collage.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] In signal processing, **sampling** is the reduction of a continuous-time signal to a discrete-time signal.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] A common example is the conversion of a sound wave to a sequence of "samples".
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] A **sample** is a value of the signal at a point in time and/or space; this definition differs from the term's usage in statistics, which refers to a set of such values.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] A **sampler** is a subsystem or operation that extracts samples from a continuous signal.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] A theoretical **ideal sampler** produces samples equivalent to the instantaneous value of the continuous signal at the desired points.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The original signal can be reconstructed from a sequence of samples, up to the Nyquist limit, by passing the sequence of samples through a reconstruction filter.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Functions of space, time, or any other dimension can be sampled, and similarly in two or more dimensions.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] For functions that vary with time, let $s(t)$ be a continuous function (or "signal") to be sampled, and let sampling be performed by measuring the value of the continuous function every T seconds, which is called the **sampling interval** or **sampling period**.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The **sampling frequency** or **sampling rate**, $f_{s}$ , is the average number of samples obtained in one second, thus $f_{s}=1/T$ , with the unit *samples per second*, sometimes referred to as hertz, for example 48 kHz is 48,000 *samples per second*.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Reconstructing a continuous function from samples is done by interpolation algorithms.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula is mathematically equivalent to an ideal low-pass filter whose input is a sequence of Dirac delta functions that are modulated (multiplied) by the sample values.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] When the time interval between adjacent samples is a constant $(T)$ , the sequence of delta functions is called a Dirac comb.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Mathematically, the modulated Dirac comb is equivalent to the product of the comb function with $s(t)$ .
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] That mathematical abstraction is sometimes referred to as *impulse sampling*.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Most sampled signals are not simply stored and reconstructed.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The fidelity of a theoretical reconstruction is a common measure of the effectiveness of sampling.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] That fidelity is reduced when $s(t)$ contains frequency components whose cycle length (period) is less than 2 sample intervals (see *Aliasing*).
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The corresponding frequency limit, in *cycles per second* (hertz), is $0.5$ cycle/sample × $f_{s}$ samples/second = $f_{s}/2$ , known as the Nyquist frequency of the sampler.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Therefore, $s(t)$ is usually the output of a low-pass filter, functionally known as an *anti-aliasing filter*.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Without an anti-aliasing filter, frequencies higher than the Nyquist frequency will influence the samples in a way that is misinterpreted by the interpolation process.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] In practice, the continuous signal is sampled using an analog-to-digital converter (ADC), a device with various physical limitations.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] This results in deviations from the theoretically perfect reconstruction, collectively referred to as distortion.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Although the use of oversampling can completely eliminate aperture error and aliasing by shifting them out of the passband, this technique cannot be practically used above a few GHz, and may be prohibitively expensive at much lower frequencies.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Furthermore, while oversampling can reduce quantization error and non-linearity, it cannot eliminate these entirely.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Consequently, practical ADCs at audio frequencies typically do not exhibit aliasing or aperture error, and are not limited by quantization error.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] At RF and microwave frequencies, where oversampling is impractical and filters are expensive, aperture error, quantization error and aliasing can be significant limitations.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Jitter, noise, and quantization are often analyzed by modeling them as random errors added to the sample values.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Integration and zero-order hold effects can be analyzed as a form of low-pass filtering.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The non-linearities of either ADC or DAC are analyzed by replacing the ideal linear function mapping with a proposed nonlinear function.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Digital audio systems typically employ pulse-code modulation (PCM) to encode sound as a series of discrete samples of the electrical level of an analog audio signal.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Analog signals are captured (encoded) as PCM samples in analog-to-digital conversion (ADC), and reproduced (decoded) using digital-to-analog conversion (DAC).
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The encoding used for the storage and transmission of digitised sound data within the system may differ.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] When it is necessary to capture audio covering the entire 20–20,000 Hz range of human hearing such as when recording music or many types of acoustic events, audio waveforms are typically sampled at 44.1 kHz (CD), 48 kHz, 88.2 kHz, or 96 kHz.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The approximately double-rate requirement is a consequence of the Nyquist theorem.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Sampling rates higher than about 50 kHz to 60 kHz cannot supply more usable information for human listeners.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Early professional audio equipment manufacturers chose sampling rates in the region of 40 to 50 kHz for this reason.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Conversely, ultrasonic sounds may interact with and modulate the audible part of the frequency spectrum (intermodulation distortion), *degrading* the fidelity.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] One advantage of higher sampling rates is that they can relax the low-pass filter design requirements for ADCs and DACs, but with modern oversampling delta-sigma-converters, this advantage is less important.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The Audio Engineering Society recommends 48 kHz sampling rate for most applications, but gives recognition to 44.1 kHz for CD and other consumer uses, 32 kHz for transmission-related applications, and 96 kHz for higher bandwidth or relaxed anti-aliasing filtering.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Robert Stuart state that the ideal sampling rate would be about 60 kHz, but since this is not a standard frequency, recommend 88.2 or 96 kHz for recording purposes.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Audio is typically recorded at 8-, 16-, and 24-bit depth; which yield a theoretical maximum signal-to-quantization-noise ratio (SQNR) for a pure sine wave of, approximately; 49.93 dB, 98.09 dB, and 122.17 dB.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Thermal noise limits the true number of bits that can be used in quantization.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Few analog systems have signal to noise ratios (SNR) exceeding 120 dB.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] However, digital signal processing operations can have very high dynamic range, consequently, it is common to perform mixing and mastering operations at 32-bit floating-point precision and then convert to 16- or 24-bit for distribution.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Speech signals, i.e., signals intended to carry only human speech, can usually be sampled at a much lower rate.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] For most phonemes, almost all of the energy is contained in the 100 Hz – 4 kHz range, allowing a sampling rate of 8 kHz.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] This is the sampling rate used by nearly all telephony systems, which use the G.711 sampling and quantization specifications.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Standard-definition television (SDTV) uses either 720 by 480 pixels (US NTSC 525-line) or 720 by 576 pixels (UK PAL 625-line) for the visible picture area.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] High-definition television (HDTV) uses 720p (progressive), 1080i (interlaced), and 1080p (progressive, also known as Full-HD).
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] In digital video, the temporal sampling rate is defined as the frame rate – or rather the field rate – rather than the notional pixel clock.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The image sampling frequency is the repetition rate of the sensor integration period.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Video digital-to-analog converters operate in the megahertz range (from ~3 MHz for low-quality composite video scalers in early game consoles, to 250 MHz or more for the highest-resolution VGA output).
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] When analog video is converted to digital video, a different sampling process occurs, this time at the pixel frequency, corresponding to a spatial sampling rate along scan lines.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial sampling in the other direction is determined by the spacing of scan lines in the raster.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The sampling rates and resolutions in both spatial directions can be measured in units of lines per picture height.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Spatial aliasing of high-frequency luma or chroma video components shows up as a moiré pattern.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The process of volume rendering samples a 3D grid of voxels to produce 3D renderings of sliced (tomographic) data.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The 3D grid is assumed to represent a continuous region of 3D space.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Volume rendering is common in medical imaging, X-ray computed tomography (CT/CAT), magnetic resonance imaging (MRI), positron emission tomography (PET) are some examples.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] It is also used for seismic tomography and other applications.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] When a bandpass signal is sampled slower than its Nyquist rate, the samples are indistinguishable from samples of a low-frequency alias of the high-frequency signal.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] That is often done purposefully in such a way that the lowest-frequency alias satisfies the Nyquist criterion, because the bandpass signal is still uniquely represented and recoverable.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Oversampling is used in most modern analog-to-digital converters to reduce the distortion introduced by practical digital-to-analog converters, such as a zero-order hold instead of idealizations like the Whittaker–Shannon interpolation formula.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Although complex-valued samples can be obtained as described above, they are also created by manipulating samples of a real-valued waveform.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] For instance, the equivalent baseband waveform can be created without explicitly computing ${\hat {s}}(t)$ , by processing the product sequence, $\left[s(nT)\cdot e^{-i2\pi {\frac {B}{2}}Tn}\right]$ , through a digital low-pass filter whose cutoff frequency is $B/2$ .
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] Computing only every other sample of the output sequence reduces the sample rate commensurate with the reduced Nyquist rate.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] The result is half as many complex-valued samples as the original number of real samples.
[src:granular-synthesis/sampling-signal-processing] No information is lost, and the original $s(t)$ waveform can be recovered, if necessary.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A **synthesizer** (also **synthesiser** or **synth**) is an electronic musical instrument that generates audio signals.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers typically create sounds by generating waveforms through methods including subtractive synthesis, additive synthesis, and frequency modulation synthesis.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] These sounds may be altered by components such as filters, which cut or boost frequencies; envelopes, which control articulation, or how notes begin and end; and low-frequency oscillators, which modulate parameters such as pitch, volume, or filter characteristics affecting timbre.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are typically played with keyboards or controlled by sequencers, software or other instruments, and can be synchronized to other equipment via MIDI.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer-like instruments emerged in the United States in the mid-20th century with instruments such as the RCA Mark II, which was controlled with punch cards and used hundreds of vacuum tubes.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog synthesizer, developed by Robert Moog and first sold in 1964, is credited for pioneering concepts such as voltage-controlled oscillators, envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, the smaller, cheaper Minimoog standardized synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards, unlike the larger modular synthesizers before it.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, which used microprocessors to allow users to store sounds for the first time.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments, was introduced in 1982 and remains an industry standard.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, launched in 1983, was a major success and popularized digital synthesis.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Software synthesizers now can be run as plug-ins or embedded on microchips.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 21st century, analog synthesizers returned to popularity with the advent of cheaper manufacturing.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were initially viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and countercultural scenes but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968)*,* a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, took synthesizers to the mainstream.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They were adopted by electronic acts and pop and rock groups in the 1960s and 1970s and were widely used in 1980s music.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced genres such as electronic and hip hop music.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is used in nearly every genre and is considered one of the most important instruments in the music industry.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] As electricity became more widely available, the early 20th century saw the invention of electronic musical instruments including the Telharmonium, Trautonium, ondes Martenot and theremin.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1930s, the Hammond Organ Company built the Novachord, a large instrument powered by 72 voltage-controlled amplifiers and 146 vacuum tubes.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1948, the Canadian engineer Hugh Le Caine completed the electronic sackbut, a precursor to voltage-controlled synthesizers, with keyboard sensitivity allowing for vibrato, glissando, and attack control.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1957, Harry Olson and Herbert Belar completed the RCA Mark II Sound Synthesizer at the RCA laboratories in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The instrument read punched paper tape that controlled an analog synthesizer containing 750 vacuum tubes.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was acquired by the Columbia-Princeton Electronic Music Center and used almost exclusively by Milton Babbitt, a composer at Princeton University.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* define "the early years of the synthesizer" as between 1964 and the mid-1970s, beginning with the debut of the Moog synthesizer, designed by the American engineer Robert Moog.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was composed of separate modules connected by patch cables that generate, shape or control sound.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog developed a means of controlling pitch through voltage, the voltage-controlled oscillator.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This, along with Moog components such as envelopes, noise generators, filters, and sequencers, became standard components in synthesizers.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Around the same period, the American engineer Don Buchla created the Buchla Modular Electronic Music System.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Instead of a conventional keyboard, Buchla's system used touchplates which transmitted control voltages depending on finger position and force.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, the Moog's keyboard made it more accessible and marketable to musicians, and keyboards became the standard means of controlling synthesizers.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Moog and Buchla initially avoided the word *synthesizer* for their instruments, as it was associated with the RCA synthesizer; however, by the 1970s, it had become the standard term.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1970, Moog launched a cheaper, smaller synthesizer, the Minimoog.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It was the first synthesizer sold in music stores, and was more practical for live performance.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It standardized the concept of synthesizers as self-contained instruments with built-in keyboards.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the early 1970s, the British composer Ken Freeman introduced the first string synthesizer, designed to emulate string sections.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] After retail stores started selling synthesizers in 1971, other synthesizer companies were established, including ARP in the US and EMS in the UK.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP's products included the ARP 2600, which folded into a carrying case and had built-in speakers, and the Odyssey, a rival to the Minimoog.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The less expensive EMS synthesizers were used by European art rock and progressive rock acts including Brian Eno and Pink Floyd.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Designs for synthesizers appeared in the amateur electronics market, such as a design published in *Practical Electronics* in 1973.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] By the mid-1970s, ARP was the world's largest synthesizer manufacturer, though it closed in 1981.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were monophonic, meaning they could only play one note at a time.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Some of the earliest commercial polyphonic synthesizers were created by the American engineer Tom Oberheim, such as the OB-X (1979).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1978, the American company Sequential Circuits released the Prophet-5, the first fully programmable polyphonic synthesizer.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Whereas previous synthesizers required users to adjust cables and knobs to change sounds, with no guarantee of exactly recreating a sound, the Prophet-5 used microprocessors to store sounds in patch memory.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This facilitated a move from synthesizers creating unpredictable sounds to producing "a standard package of familiar sounds".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The synthesizer market grew dramatically in the 1980s.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] 1982 saw the introduction of MIDI, a standardized means of synchronizing electronic instruments; it remains an industry standard.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] An influential sampling synthesizer, the Fairlight CMI, was released in 1979, with the ability to record and play back samples at different pitches.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Though its high price made it inaccessible to amateurs, it was adopted by high-profile pop musicians including Kate Bush and Peter Gabriel.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The success of the Fairlight drove competition, improving sampling technology and lowering prices.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early competing samplers included the E-mu Emulator in 1981 and the Akai S-series in 1985.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1983, Yamaha released the first commercially successful digital synthesizer, the Yamaha DX7.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Based on frequency modulation (FM) synthesis developed by the Stanford University engineer John Chowning, the DX7 was characterized by its *harsh*, *glassy* and *chilly* sounds, compared to the *warm* and *fuzzy* sounds of analog synthesis.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The DX7 was the first synthesizer to sell more than 100,000 unitsand remains one of the bestselling in history.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Digital synthesizers typically contained preset sounds emulating acoustic instruments, with algorithms controlled with menus and buttons.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Synclavier, made with FM technology licensed from Yamaha, offered features such as 16-bit sampling and digital recording.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With a starting price of $13,000, its use was limited to universities, studios and wealthy artists.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Roland D-50 (1987) blended Roland's linear arithmetic algorithm with samples, and was the first mass-produced synthesizer with built-in digital effects such as delay, reverb and chorus.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1988, the Japanese manufacturer Korg released the M1, a digital synthesizer workstation featuring sampled transients and loops.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With more than 250,000 units sold, it remains the bestselling synthesizer in history.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The advent of digital synthesizers led to a downturn in interest in analog synthesizers in the following decade.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ReBirth by Propellerhead Software and Reality by Seer Systems, the first software synthesizers that could be played in real time via MIDI, were released in 1997.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1999, an update to the music software Cubase allowed users to run software instruments (including synthesizers) as plug-ins, triggering a wave of new software instruments.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Propellerhead's Reason, released in 2000, introduced an array of recognizable virtual studio equipment.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The market for patchable and modular synthesizers rebounded in the late 1990s.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2000s, older analog synthesizers regained popularity, sometimes selling for much more than their original prices.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 2010s, new, affordable analog synthesizers were introduced by companies including Moog, Korg, Arturia and Dave Smith Instruments.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The renewed interest is credited to the appeal of imperfect *organic* sounds and simpler interfaces, and modern surface-mount technology making analog synthesizers cheaper and faster to manufacture.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers were viewed as avant-garde, valued by the 1960s psychedelic and counter-cultural scenes for their ability to make new sounds, but with little perceived commercial potential.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] *Switched-On Bach* (1968), a bestselling album of Bach compositions arranged for Moog synthesizer by Wendy Carlos, demonstrated that synthesizers could be more than "random noise machines", taking them to the mainstream.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, debates were held about the appropriateness of synthesizers in baroque music, and according to the *Guardian* they were quickly abandoned in "serious classical circles".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Today, the synthesizer is one of the most important instruments in the music industry, used in nearly every genre.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] It is considered by the authors of *Analog Days* as "the only innovation that can stand alongside the electric guitar as a great new instrument of the age of electricity ...
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Moog was adopted by 1960s rock acts including the Doors, the Grateful Dead, the Rolling Stones, the Beatles, and Keith Emerson.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Emerson was the first major rock musician to perform with the Moog and it became a trademark of his performances, helping take his band Emerson, Lake & Palmer to global stardom.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] According to *Analog Days*, the likes of Emerson, with his Moog performances, "did for the keyboard what Jimi Hendrix did for the guitar".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] String synthesizers were used by 1970s progressive rock bands including Camel, Caravan, Electric Light Orchestra, Gentle Giant and Renaissance.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The portable Minimoog (1970), much smaller than the modular synthesizers before it, made synthesizers more common in live performance.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Early synthesizers could only play one note at a time, making them suitable for basslines, leads and solos.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With the rise of polyphonic synthesizers in the 1970s and 1980s, "the keyboard in rock once more started to revert to the background, to be used for fills and atmosphere rather than for soloing".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Queen included statements in their 1970s album notes specifying that no synthesisers had been used, but added them in their 1980 album *The Game*.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Minimoog took a place in mainstream African-American music, most notably in the work of Stevie Wonder, and in jazz, such as the work of Sun Ra.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the late 1970s and the early 1980s, the Minimoog was widely used in the emerging disco genre by artists including Abba and Giorgio Moroder.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Sampling, introduced with the Fairlight synthesizer in 1979, has influenced all genres of music and had a major influence on the development of electronic and hip hop music.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s, electronic music composers such as Jean Michel Jarre and Isao Tomita released successful synthesizer-led instrumental albums.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] This influenced the emergence of synth-pop from the late 1970s to the early 1980s.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The sequencer-based Roland TB-303 (1981), in conjunction with the Roland TR-808 and TR-909 drum machines, became a foundation of electronic dance music genres such as house and techno when producers acquired cheap second-hand units later in the decade.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The authors of *Analog Days* connect the synthesizer's origins in 1960s psychedelia to the raves and British Second Summer of Love of the 1980s and the club scenes of the 1990s and 2000s.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Gary Numan's 1979 hits "Are 'Friends' Electric?" and "Cars" made heavy use of synthesizers.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] OMD's "Enola Gay" (1980) used distinctive electronic percussion and a synthesized melody.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Soft Cell used a synthesized melody on their 1981 hit "Tainted Love".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Nick Rhodes, the keyboardist of Duran Duran, used synthesizers including the Roland Jupiter-4 and Jupiter-8.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Chart hits include Depeche Mode's "Just Can't Get Enough" (1981), the Human League's "Don't You Want Me" and works by Ultravox.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, digital synthesizers were widely used in pop music.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The Yamaha DX7, released in 1983, became a pop staple, used on songs by A-ha, Kenny Loggins, Kool & the Gang.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Its E PIANO 1 preset became particularly famous, especially for power ballads, and was used by artists including Whitney Houston, Chicago, Prince, Phil Collins, Luther Vandross, Billy Ocean, and Celine Dion.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Korg M1 presets were widely used in 1990s house music, beginning with Madonna's 1990 single "Vogue".
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are common in film and television soundtracks.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1969, Mort Garson used a Moog to compose a soundtrack for the televised footage of the Apollo 11 moonwalk, creating a link between electronic music and space in the American popular imagination.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] ARP synthesizers were used to create sound effects for the 1977 science fiction films *Close Encounters of the Third Kind* and *Star Wars*, including the voice of the robot R2-D2.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1970s and 1980s, synthesizers were used in the scores for thrillers and horror films including *A Clockwork Orange* (1971), *Apocalypse Now* (1979), *The Fog* (1980) and *Manhunter* (1986).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Brad Fiedel used a Prophet synthesizer to record the soundtrack for *The Terminator* (1984), and the filmmaker John Carpenter used them extensively for his soundtracks.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers were used to create themes for television shows including *Knight Rider* (1982)*, Twin Peaks* (1990) and *Stranger Things* (2016).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The rise of the synthesizer led to major changes in the music industry, including job displacement, comparable to the 1920s arrival of sound in film, which put live musicians accompanying silent films out of work.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] With its ability to imitate instruments such as strings and horns, the synthesizer threatened the jobs of session musicians by allowing one keyboardist or music programmer to produce the same range of sounds as an entire orchestra.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] For a period, the Moog was banned from use in union work, a restriction negotiated by the American Federation of Musicians (AFM).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The musician Walter Sear persuaded the AFM that the synthesizer demanded skill, and the category of *synthesizer player* was accepted into the union.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] However, players were subject to "suspicion and hostility" for years.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1982, following a tour by Barry Manilow using synthesizers instead of an orchestra, the British Musicians' Union attempted to ban synthesizers, attracting controversy.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In the 1980s, a few musicians skilled at programming the Yamaha DX7 found employment creating sounds for other acts.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers generate audio through various forms of analog and digital synthesis.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Oscillators produce waveforms (such as sawtooth, sine, or pulse waves) with different timbres.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Voltage-controlled amplifiers (VCAs) control the volume or gain of the audio signal.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] VCAs can be modulated by other components, such as LFOs and envelopes.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] A VCA is a preamp that boosts (amplifies) the electronic signal before passing it on to an external or built-in power amplifier, as well as a means to control its amplitude (volume) using an attenuator.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] The gain of the VCA is affected by a *control voltage* (CV), coming from an envelope generator, an LFO, the keyboard or some other source.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Envelopes control how sounds change over time.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They may control parameters such as amplitude (volume), filters (frequencies), or pitch.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Low-frequency oscillators (LFOs) produce waveforms used to modulate parameters, such as the pitch of oscillators (producing vibrato).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters remove frequencies from the audio signal, similarly to equalization, to shape sounds.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They typically include controls to set the point at which frequencies are attenuated, and to add resonance.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Common types include low-pass filters, which remove audio above a specified frequency, and high-pass filters, which do the opposite.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Filters may be controlled with envelopes or LFOs.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Arpeggiators take input chords and convert them into arpeggios.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] They usually include controls for speed, range and mode (the movement of the arpeggio).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizers are often controlled with electronic or digital keyboards or MIDI controller keyboards, which may be built into the synthesizer unit or attached via connections such as CV/gate, USB, or MIDI.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Keyboards may offer expression such as velocity sensitivity and aftertouch, allowing for more control over the sound.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Synthesizer clones are unlicensed recreations of previous synthesizers, often marketed as affordable versions of famous musical equipment.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Clones are available as physical instruments and software.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Companies that have sold software clones include Arturia and Native Instruments.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Behringer manufactures equipment modelled on instruments including the Minimoog, Pro-One, and TB-303, and drum machines such as the TR-808.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Other synthesizer clones include the MiniMOD (a series of Eurorack modules based on the Minimoog), the Intellijel Atlantis (based on the SH-101), and the x0x Heart (based on the TB-303).
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] Creating clones of older hardware is legal where the patents have expired.
[src:granular-synthesis/sound-synthesis] In 1997, Mackie lost their lawsuit against Behringer as copyright law in the United States did not cover their circuit board designs.
